    <div class="card">
      <h2>Comprehensive Guide</h2>
      <p>Cinnamon is harvested from the inner bark of tree species from the genus <em>Cinnamomum</em>. It is one of the few spices used equally in sweet and savory applications globally.</p>
    <h3>Ceylon vs Cassia</h3>
    <p>Ceylon (true cinnamon) from Sri Lanka is mild, complex, citrusy, and has a fragile, crumbly bark. Cassia (typically sold in the US) is stronger, spicier, and has thick, hard bark that curves inward from both sides.</p>
    <h3>Sweet vs Savory</h3>
    <p>While Western cuisines use cinnamon primarily for baking and desserts, Middle Eastern, North African, and South Asian cuisines heavily feature it in savory dishes like chili, tagines, pho, and curries.</p>
    <h3>Coumarin Content</h3>
    <p>Cassia cinnamon contains high levels of coumarin, a compound that can be toxic to the liver in very large, sustained doses. Ceylon cinnamon has only trace, negligible amounts of coumarin.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <h3>What is the difference between Ceylon and Cassia cinnamon?</h3><p>Ceylon is 'true cinnamon,' sweeter and more delicate. Cassia is bolder, spicier, and the standard in grocery stores.</p><h3>Can I use cinnamon in savory dishes?</h3><p>Absolutely. Cinnamon is a key component in savory dishes like Moroccan tagines, Cincinnati chili, and Indian curries.</p><h3>How long do cinnamon sticks last?</h3><p>Stored properly in an airtight container away from light and heat, whole cinnamon sticks can retain their flavor for up to 3-4 years.</p>
